My department recently opened a dialogue about grading. This reminded me of a classic Peter Elbow essay entitled &ldquo;Ranking, Evaluating, Liking: Sorting Out Three forms of Judgment.&rdquo;
In one key passage, Elbow argues that too much of an emphasis on evaluation disrupts learning:
Most important of all, evaluation harms the climate for learning and teaching&mdash;or rather too much evaluation has this effect. That is, if we evaluate everything students write, they tend to remain tangled up in the assumption that their whole job in school is to give teachers &ldquo;what they want.

 &ldquo;Our field-records will be perhaps the most valuable of all our results; hence the importance of a convenient system of record.&rdquo;
— Joseph Grinnell, 1908
Field Notes The central metaphor for this course is the field note.

WR3 | Workshops Cutting Corners in Research I can&rsquo;t tell you the number of times a first-year student has waited until the other students left the classroom in order to approach me and sheepishly ask this question: &ldquo;Professor, if I get a book from the library or download an article for my research project, do I have to read the whole thing?&rdquo;
Don&rsquo;t be silly; of course not.
And I&rsquo;ll tell you a secret: professors don&rsquo;t read everything in their field(s) of study either.

WR3 | Workshops Introduction to Academic Research &ldquo;The problem is that doing scholarly work is intrinsically a mess.&rdquo;
&mdash; Kieran Healy
Perhaps the most common feature of books designed to help students do academic research is their dishonesty. These textbooks present academic research as an orderly list of procedures and tasks, each one leading logically to the next, culminating in a superbly crafted essay. This narrative generally begins with the formulation of a research question, proceeds to the gathering of background information and secondary sources, and finally to the drafting, revision, and completion of the project.
